default&#xa0;default1.1 defaultThe evidence presented in this paper is based on research which involved conducting 30 interviews with local authority officers, 
defaultacademy 
defaultsponsors, 
defaultacademy 
defaultprincipals and chairs of governors. Interviews 
defaultexplored
default the local implementation of the academies policy in two local authority case study areas and were conducted between September 2012 and April 2013. 
defaultThe research focused on
default the
default implementation of the
default academies policy in secondary schools. The first case study is a Metropolitan authority in the North-West of England (hereafter referred to as NW-LA). The research 
defaultin NW-LA 
defaultfocused on interviewing principals and sponsors of academies which were set up under the New Labour government as well as local authority officers
default (current and retired)
default. The second case study is a shire county in the East of England (hereafter referred to as E-LA) which has amongst the highest number of secondary
default school
default converters in the country. Interviews conducted in E-LA focused on principals and chairs of governors of converter academies and 
defaultcurrent
default 
defaultlocal authority officers. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe research is part of a PhD project funded by the Economic and Social Research Council 
default[grant number ESI01943X/1].
